  "title": "Universally Converging Representations of Matter Across Scientific Foundation Models",
  "experiments_summary": "The study analyzes hidden-state representations from approximately 50 scientific foundation models across molecules, materials, and proteins using multiple datasets and alignment metrics. Models examined include: (1) Machine-learning Interatomic Potentials (MLIPs) with equivariant architectures (MACE, EquiformerV2/EqV2, eSEN) and non-equivariant architectures (Orb family - V2, V3 conservative and direct variants); (2) Universal Models for Atoms (UMA) trained jointly on molecules and materials; (3) Lightweight representation encoder Geom2Vec; (4) Text/sequence encoders including ChemBERTa, MolFormer, and ChemGPT operating on SMILES/SELFIES strings; (5) Natural language models (GPT OSS 20B, Qwen3 30B, DeepSeek R1); and (6) Protein models including sequence-based (ESM2) and structure-based (ProteinMPNN) models. Five datasets were used: QM9 (134k small organic molecules with DFT properties), sAlex (subsampled Alexandria inorganic materials), OMat24 (118M inorganic materials structures), OMol25 (>100M molecules, used as out-of-distribution), and RCSB Protein Data Bank (filtered to ~48,530 sequence-structure pairs). Embeddings were extracted from the last hidden layer of each model by inputting structures as ASE atoms, graphs, or SMILES strings, with node-level features averaged to obtain structure-wide embeddings. Three alignment metrics were employed: Centered Kernel Nearest Neighbor Alignment (CKNNA) for local neighborhood similarity, Intrinsic Dimension Correlation (IDCor) for global manifold mutual information, and Information Imbalance for asymmetric information content comparison. Analysis involved computing pairwise CKNNA and IDCor between all model pairs, calculating intrinsic dimensions for each model's embeddings, constructing phylogenetic trees using CKNNA-derived distances, and comparing in-distribution (OMat24, sAlex) versus out-of-distribution (OMol25) alignment patterns. Approximately 50,000 randomly sampled embeddings per dataset were analyzed, with correlation matrices generated and block-diagonalized by architecture family to visualize cross-modality and cross-architecture alignment patterns."
